xxl.core.indexStructures

Class IndexedSet<IndexStructure extends Tree,E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • xxl.core.indexStructures.IndexedSet<IndexStructure,E>
  • Type Parameters:
    IndexStructure - The underlying implementation of a tree index structure
    E - The data type which should be managed
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Set<E>, SortedSet<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    BPlusIndexedSet

    public abstract class IndexedSet<IndexStructure extends Tree,E>
extends Object
implements SortedSet<E>
    The abstract base class IndexedSet is a Java SortedSet implementation to wrap the abilities of various index structures in order to act like a normal Java SortedSet. With this it is possible to use a set independent of the underlying (tree) index type and without a deeper knowledge how to use the index structure exactly.

      • IndexedSet

        public IndexedSet(IndexStructure tree,
                  IndexBuilder creator)
        Sets up a new instance of IndexedSet with a given implementation of a tree index and it's builder object. The builder instance contains different meta data for the index, e.g. the file path, the data type, containers and others.
        Parameters:
        tree - An instance of an index structure
        creator - The builder which created the index structure

    • Method Detail

      • getFilePath

        public String getFilePath()
        Depending on the index type some data will be stored to hard drive during run time or persistently if the index supports the saving of it's content.
        Returns:
        Directory in file system which will contain the data of the index structure

      • getIndexStructure

        public IndexStructure getIndexStructure()
        Returns the underlying index structure. Please note: Although it is more flexible to perform queries directly with the underlying index structure it is not recommended to access it. Because of performance reasons some methods e.g. Set.size() may be calculated by the IndexedSet sub class and not by querying the underlying tree. If you manipulate the content of the index structure by hand some methods of the wrapping IndexedSet may produce unexpected output.
        Returns:
        A (editable) direct reference to the underlying index structure.

      • save

        public void save()
          throws IOException
        Stores the content of this set to hard drive. Please note: Depending on the underlying index structure this method only flushes buffers. It is possible that unsaved changes after a save() call will also be available in future without another save() call. But calling save() ensures that the entire content of the set is stored and changes will not be missed if the set is dropped from the computers main memory.
        Throws:
        IOException - If something went wrong during IO

      • sizeBigInteger

        public abstract BigInteger sizeBigInteger()
        Returns the size of the current set as BigInteger. Dependent on the underlying index structure the content amount is only limited by the hard drive capacity. It may comes to an overflow for standard Integer data which contains the set size. This methods guarantees the correct set size.
        Returns:
        The set size
